Under the Food Hygiene Rating Scheme, establishments preparing and serving food are given a star rating for hygiene.

Public health minister Jane Ellison said it 'provides transparency to consumers on hygiene standards in places where they eat or buy food'.

The best rated sites are given five stars and a named 'very good'. Four stars awarded for 'good' levels of hygiene, and three stars for being 'generally satisfactory'.

However, two stars mean improvement is required, one star means 'major improvement required' and zero stars suggests 'urgent action required'.

According to figures released in Parliament, more than 500 hospitals, childcare and caring premises have been given two or fewer stars.

